    "# Notebook 12 — Phylogenetic Trees: Neighbour-Joining\n",
    "\n",
    "**Module:** 08 — Bioinformatics: Sequence Analysis  \n",
    "**Notebook:** 12 of 18  \n",
    "**Time estimate:** 75 minutes\n",
    "\n",
    "> NJ is the production-standard distance-based method. Know the Q-matrix\n",
    "> correction and why it is rate-corrected where UPGMA is not."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 1 — Motivation\n",
    "\n",
    "UPGMA assumes a molecular clock. Neighbour-Joining does not. For most real biological\n",
    "data — where different lineages evolve at different rates — NJ produces a more accurate\n",
    "unrooted tree. It was published by Saitou & Nei (1987) and remains one of the most\n",
    "widely cited methods in all of biology."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 2 — Intuition\n",
    "\n",
    "NJ's key departure from UPGMA: instead of merging the two *most similar* sequences,\n",
    "merge the two sequences that are **most similar relative to their similarity to\n",
    "everything else** (the Q-matrix transformation).\n",
    "\n",
    "Why? If taxon A is generally similar to all others (short external branch), then\n",
    "A–B being close might just reflect A's short branch, not a specific A–B relationship.\n",
    "The Q-matrix corrects for this by subtracting the average distance of each taxon to\n",
    "all others.\n",
    "\n",
    "The resulting tree is **unrooted** — NJ does not assume a clock. Rooting requires\n",
    "either an outgroup or a separate root-finding method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 3 — Biological Background\n",
    "\n",
    "Rate variation across lineages is the rule, not the exception:\n",
    "- Birds evolve faster than turtles\n",
    "- Rapidly-evolving HIV vs. slowly-evolving large DNA viruses\n",
    "- Mitochondrial DNA vs. nuclear DNA in the same species\n",
    "\n",
    "NJ is **statistically consistent**: given enough data, it converges to the true tree.\n",
    "UPGMA is not consistent when rates vary. This is why NJ (or its descendants like\n",
    "FastTree and RAxML's distance init) is used for real data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Bootstrap support:** A standard NJ analysis resamples columns from the MSA\n",
    "(bootstrap), rebuilds the tree, and reports how often each clade appears. Support\n",
    ">70% is generally considered reliable."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 4 — Mathematical Explanation\n",
    "\n",
    "**NJ Algorithm:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Compute the Q-matrix:\n",
    "   $$Q[i][j] = (n-2) D[i][j] - \\sum_{k} D[i][k] - \\sum_{k} D[j][k]$$\n",
    "   where $n$ is the number of active taxa.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Find $(i,j)$ minimising $Q[i][j]$.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Compute branch lengths to the new internal node $u$:\n",
    "   $$d(i, u) = \\frac{D[i][j]}{2} + \\frac{\\sum_k D[i][k] - \\sum_k D[j][k]}{2(n-2)}$$\n",
    "   $$d(j, u) = D[i][j] - d(i, u)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Update distances to new node $u$:\n",
    "   $$D[u][k] = \\frac{D[i][k] + D[j][k] - D[i][j]}{2}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Remove $i, j$; add $u$; repeat until 2 nodes remain; connect them.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Key:** step 3 can produce negative branch lengths if the distance matrix violates\n",
    "the four-point condition — typically treated as 0 in practice."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Step 6 — Python Implementation\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from dataclasses import dataclass\n",
    "from typing import Optional\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "@dataclass\n",
    "class NJNode:\n",
    "    name: str\n",
    "    left: Optional['NJNode'] = None\n",
    "    right: Optional['NJNode'] = None\n",
    "    left_dist: float = 0.0\n",
    "    right_dist: float = 0.0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def is_leaf(self):\n",
    "        return self.left is None and self.right is None\n",
    "\n",
    "    def to_newick(self) -> str:\n",
    "        if self.is_leaf():\n",
    "            return self.name\n",
    "        l = self.left.to_newick()\n",
    "        r = self.right.to_newick()\n",
    "        return f'({l}:{self.left_dist:.4f},{r}:{self.right_dist:.4f})'\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def neighbour_joining(dist_matrix: np.ndarray, names: list[str]) -> NJNode:\n",
    "    n_orig = len(names)\n",
    "    D = dist_matrix.copy().astype(float)\n",
    "    nodes = [NJNode(name=name) for name in names]\n",
    "    active = list(range(n_orig))\n",
    "    next_idx = n_orig  # for new internal nodes\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Expand D to accommodate internal nodes\n",
    "    max_nodes = 2 * n_orig\n",
    "    big_D = np.zeros((max_nodes, max_nodes))\n",
    "    big_D[:n_orig, :n_orig] = D\n",
    "    D = big_D\n",
    "    nodes.extend([None] * (max_nodes - n_orig))\n",
    "\n",
    "    while len(active) > 2:\n",
    "        n = len(active)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Compute row sums for active taxa\n",
    "        row_sum = {i: sum(D[i, j] for j in active if j != i) for i in active}\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Q matrix\n",
    "        min_q = float('inf')\n",
    "        min_i, min_j = -1, -1\n",
    "        for a_idx in range(len(active)):\n",
    "            for b_idx in range(a_idx + 1, len(active)):\n",
    "                i, j = active[a_idx], active[b_idx]\n",
    "                q = (n - 2) * D[i, j] - row_sum[i] - row_sum[j]\n",
    "                if q < min_q:\n",
    "                    min_q = q\n",
    "                    min_i, min_j = i, j\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Branch lengths to new internal node\n",
    "        d_ij = D[min_i, min_j]\n",
    "        if n > 2:\n",
    "            branch_i = d_ij / 2 + (row_sum[min_i] - row_sum[min_j]) / (2 * (n - 2))\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            branch_i = d_ij / 2\n",
    "        branch_j = d_ij - branch_i\n",
    "        branch_i = max(0.0, branch_i)\n",
    "        branch_j = max(0.0, branch_j)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # New node\n",
    "        new_node = NJNode(\n",
    "            name=f'internal_{next_idx}',\n",
    "            left=nodes[min_i],\n",
    "            right=nodes[min_j],\n",
    "            left_dist=branch_i,\n",
    "            right_dist=branch_j\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        nodes[next_idx] = new_node\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Update distances to new node\n",
    "        for k in active:\n",
    "            if k == min_i or k == min_j:\n",
    "                continue\n",
    "            new_d = (D[min_i, k] + D[min_j, k] - d_ij) / 2\n",
    "            D[next_idx, k] = new_d\n",
    "            D[k, next_idx] = new_d\n",
    "\n",
    "        active.remove(min_i)\n",
    "        active.remove(min_j)\n",
    "        active.append(next_idx)\n",
    "        next_idx += 1\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Connect last two nodes\n",
    "    if len(active) == 2:\n",
    "        i, j = active\n",
    "        root = NJNode(\n",
    "            name='root',\n",
    "            left=nodes[i],\n",
    "            right=nodes[j],\n",
    "            left_dist=max(0.0, D[i, j] / 2),\n",
    "            right_dist=max(0.0, D[i, j] / 2)\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        return root\n",
    "    return nodes[active[0]]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test with Saitou & Nei (1987) example\n",
    "# Distance matrix from the original NJ paper\n",
    "names_sn = ['OTU1', 'OTU2', 'OTU3', 'OTU4', 'OTU5', 'OTU6']\n",
    "D_sn = np.array([\n",
    "    [0, 5, 4, 7, 6, 8],\n",
    "    [5, 0, 7, 10, 9, 11],\n",
    "    [4, 7, 0, 7, 6, 8],\n",
    "    [7, 10, 7, 0, 5, 9],\n",
    "    [6, 9, 6, 5, 0, 8],\n",
    "    [8, 11, 8, 9, 8, 0],\n",
    "], dtype=float)\n",
    "\n",
    "tree_nj = neighbour_joining(D_sn, names_sn)\n",
    "print(\"NJ tree (Newick):\")\n",
    "print(tree_nj.to_newick())\n",
    "print(\"\\nExpected groupings: (OTU1,OTU3), (OTU4,OTU5) are close pairs\")"
   ]
  },
